_torch_light.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"353" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"744" data-file-height=3D"1052"></a>=
<figcaption>Conic sections visualized with torch light</figcaption></figure=
>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conics-Converge-Diverge.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img alt=3D"2D side view of cone being sectioned by planes at=
 three different angles. The ellipse converges on the opposite side and so =
closes around the cone to form a closed profile. The hyperbola is parallel =
with the opposite side of the cone and so it never closes around it and the=
 open ends extend to infinity. The hyperbola diverges from the opposite sid=
e. so it looks like the parabola but also has another part where it interse=
cts with a mirror image of the cone" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Conics-Converge-Diverge.jpg/250px-Conics-Converg=
e-Diverge.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"263" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"965" data-file-height=3D"1014"></a><figcap=
tion>This diagram clarifies the different angles of the cutting planes that=
 result in the different properties of the three types of conic section.</f=
igcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>conic section</b>, <b>conic</b> or a <b>quadratic curve</b> is a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curve</a> obt=
ained from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conical_surface" titl=
e=3D"Conical surface">cone's surface</a> intersecting a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(mathematics)" title=3D"Plane (mathematics)">pl=
ane</a>. The three types of conic section are the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a>, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a>=
, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellips=
e">ellipse</a>; the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=
=3D"Circle">circle</a> is a special case of the ellipse, though it was some=
times considered a fourth type. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">anci=
ent Greek mathematicians</a> studied conic sections, culminating around 200=
&nbsp;BC with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_of_Perga"=
 title=3D"Apollonius of Perga">Apollonius of Perga</a>'s systematic work on=
 their properties.
</p><p>The conic sections in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
uclidean_plane" title=3D"Euclidean plane">Euclidean plane</a> have various =
distinguishing properties, many of which can be used as alternative definit=
ions.  One such property defines a non-circular conic<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section=
#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> to be the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Set_(mathematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">set</a> of those points who=
se distances to some particular point, called a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Focus_(geometry)" title=3D"Focus (geometry)">focus</a></i>=
, and some particular line, called a <i>directrix</i>, are in a fixed ratio=
, called the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentricity_(math=
ematics)" title=3D"Eccentricity (mathematics)">eccentricity</a></i>. The ty=
pe of conic is determined by the value of the eccentricity. In <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry"=
>analytic geometry</a>, a conic may be defined as a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_curve" title=3D"Algebraic curve">plane algebrai=
c curve</a> of degree 2; that is, as the set of points whose coordinates sa=
tisfy a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_equation" title=
=3D"Quadratic equation">quadratic equation</a> in two variables which can b=
e written in the form <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inli=
ne"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"di=
splay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D=
"{\displaystyle Ax^{2}+Bxy+Cy^{2}+Dx+Ey+F=3D0.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>A</mi>
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>C</mi>
        <msup>
          <mi>y</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>D</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>E</mi>
        <mi>y</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>F</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle Ax^{2}+Bxy+Cy=
^{2}+Dx+Ey+F=3D0.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c87dffa2f0e5e3eef9856689d301dc7bb5e12b51" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:39.393ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle Ax=
^{2}+Bxy+Cy^{2}+Dx+Ey+F=3D0.}"></span> The geometric properties of the coni=
c can be deduced from its equation.
</p><p>In the Euclidean plane, the three types of conic sections appear qui=
te different, but share many properties. By extending the Euclidean plane t=
o include a line at infinity, obtaining a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Projective_plane" title=3D"Projective plane">projective plane</a>, =
the apparent difference vanishes: the branches of a hyperbola meet in two p=
oints at infinity, making it a single closed curve; and the two ends of a p=
arabola meet to make it a closed curve tangent to the line at infinity. Fur=
ther extension, by expanding the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
eal_number" title=3D"Real number">real</a> coordinates to admit <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">comp=
lex</a> coordinates, provides the means to see this unification algebraical=
ly.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Euclidean_geometry">Euclide=
an geometry</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TypesOfConicSections.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/c/cc/TypesOfConicSections.jpg/250px-TypesOfConicSections.jpg" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"2048" data-file-height=3D"2048"></a><figcaption>Types of conic sectio=
ns:<br> <span class=3D"nowrap">1: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Circle" title=3D"Circle">Circle</a></span><span style=3D"padding-left:2.3em=
;">&nbsp;</span> <span class=3D"nowrap">2: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellipse">Ellipse</a></span><br> <span class=3D"n=
owrap">3: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parab=
ola">Parabola</a></span><span style=3D"padding-left:1em;">&nbsp;</span> <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap">4: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" =
title=3D"Hyperbola">Hyperbola</a></span></figcaption></figure>
<p>The conic sections have been studied for thousands of years and have pro=
vided a rich source of interesting and beautiful results in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">=
Euclidean geometry</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h3>=
</div>
<p>A conic is the curve obtained as the intersection of a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pl=
ane (geometry)">plane</a>, called the <i>cutting plane</i>, with the surfac=
e of a double <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone_(geometry)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cone (geometry)">cone</a> (a cone with two <i>n=
appes</i>). It is usually assumed that the cone is a right circular cone fo=
r the purpose of easy description, but this is not required; any double con=
e with some circular cross-section will suffice. Planes that pass through t=
he vertex of the cone will intersect the cone in a point, a line or a pair =
of intersecting lines. These are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Conic_section#Degenerate_cases"><i>degenerate</i> conics</a> and some=
 authors do not consider them to be conics at all. Unless otherwise stated,=
 "conic" in this article will refer to a non-degenerate conic.
</p><p>There are three types of conics: the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellipse">ellipse</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a>, and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a>. =
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circl=
e</a> is a special kind of ellipse, although historically Apollonius consid=
ered it a fourth type. Ellipses arise when the intersection of the cone and=
 plane is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed_curve" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Closed curve">closed curve</a>. The circle is obtain=
ed when the cutting plane is parallel to the plane of the generating circle=
 of the cone; for a right cone, this means the cutting plane is perpendicul=
ar to the axis. If the cutting plane is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Parallel_(geometry)" title=3D"Parallel (geometry)">parallel</a> to ex=
actly one generating line of the cone, then the conic is unbounded and is c=
alled a <i>parabola</i>. In the remaining case, the figure is a <i>hyperbol=
a</i>: the plane intersects <i>both</i> halves of the cone, producing two s=
eparate unbounded curves.
</p><p>Compare also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle_of_a_sp=
here" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Circle of a sphere">spheric section</a=
> (intersection of a plane with a sphere, producing a circle or point), and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_conic" title=3D"Spheric=
al conic">spherical conic</a> (intersection of an elliptic cone with a conc=
entric sphere).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Eccentricity,_focus_and_dir=
ectrix"><span id=3D"Eccentricity.2C_focus_and_directrix"></span>Eccentricit=
y, focus and directrix</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Eccentricity.png" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/0/05/Eccentricity.png/330px-Eccentricity.png" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"310" height=3D"317" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"11=
90" data-file-height=3D"1216"></a><figcaption>Conic sections of varying <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentricity_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Eccentricity (mathematics)">eccentricity</a> sharing a focus point and dire=
ctrix line, including an ellipse (red, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D=
 1/2</span>), a parabola (green, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 1</sp=
an>), and a hyperbola (blue, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 2</span>)=
. The conic of eccentricity <span class=3D"texhtml">0</span> in this figure=
 is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal" title=3D"Inf=
initesimal">infinitesimal</a> circle centered at the focus, and the conic o=
f eccentricity <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=88=9E</span> is an infinitesimal=
ly separated pair of lines.<div class=3D"paragraphbreak" style=3D"margin-to=
p:0.5em"></div> A circle of finite radius has an infinitely distant directr=
ix, while a pair of lines of finite separation have an infinitely distant f=
ocus.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Alternatively, one can define a conic section purely in terms of plane g=
eometry: it is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_(mathemat=
ics)" title=3D"Locus (mathematics)">locus</a> of all points <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> whose distance to a fix=
ed point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span>=
 (called the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focus_(geometry)" =
title=3D"Focus (geometry)">focus</a></i>) is a constant multiple <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">e</span> (called the <i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eccentricity_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Eccentricity (mathematics)">eccentricity</a></i>) of the distance from <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> to a fixed l=
ine <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span> (cal=
led the <i>directrix</i>).
For <span class=3D"texhtml">0 &lt; <i>e</i> &lt; 1</span> we obtain an elli=
pse, for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 1</span> a parabola, and for =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> &gt; 1</span> a hyperbola.
</p><p>A circle is a limiting case and is not defined by a focus and direct=
rix in the Euclidean plane. The eccentricity of a circle is defined to be z=
ero and its focus is the center of the circle, but its directrix can only b=
e taken as the line at infinity in the projective plane.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_sect=
ion#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The eccentricity of an ellipse can be seen as a measure of how far t=
he ellipse deviates from being circular.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-3"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>If the angle between the surface of the cone and its axis is <span c=
lass=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-m=
athml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"=
http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \beta }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
