  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0eefbac290198f8c31062c5907db94bd54511268" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:6.469ex; height:5.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\f=
rac {\cos \alpha }{\cos \beta }}.}"></span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note=
-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>A proof that the above curves defined by the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Dandelin_spheres#Proof_of_the_focus-directrix_property" t=
itle=3D"Dandelin spheres">focus-directrix property</a> are the same as thos=
e obtained by planes intersecting a cone is facilitated by the use of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dandelin_spheres" title=3D"Dandelin sph=
eres">Dandelin spheres</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-5"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Alternatively, an ellipse can be defined in terms of two focus point=
s, as the locus of points for which the sum of the distances to the two foc=
i is <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>a</i></span>; while a hyperbola is the loc=
us for which the difference of distances is <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>a</=
i></span>. (Here <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> is the semi-major =
axis defined below.) A parabola may also be defined in terms of its focus a=
nd latus rectum line (parallel to the directrix and passing through the foc=
us): it is the locus of points whose distance to the focus plus or minus th=
e distance to the line is equal to <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>a</i></span>=
; plus if the point is between the directrix and the latus rectum, minus ot=
herwise.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conic_parameters">Conic par=
ameters</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ellipse_parameters_2.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/7/76/Ellipse_parameters_2.svg/330px-Ellipse_parameters_2.s=
vg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"184" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"424" data-file-height=3D"251"></a><figcaption>Con=
ic parameters in the case of an ellipse</figcaption></figure>
<p>In addition to the eccentricity (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">e</span>), foci, and directrix, various geometric featur=
es and lengths are associated with a conic section.
</p><p>The <i>principal axis</i> is the line joining the foci of an ellipse=
 or hyperbola, and its midpoint is the curve's <i>center</i>. A parabola ha=
s no center.
</p><p>The <i>linear eccentricity</i> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>) is the distance between the center and a =
focus.
</p><p>The <i>latus rectum</i> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Chord_(geometry)" title=3D"Chord (geometry)">chord</a> parallel to the =
directrix and passing through a focus; its half-length is the <i>semi-latus=
 rectum</i> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=E2=
=84=93</span>).
</p><p>The <i>focal parameter</i> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">p</span>) is the distance from a focus to the correspondi=
ng directrix.
</p><p>The <i>major axis</i> is the chord between the two vertices: the lon=
gest chord of an ellipse, the shortest chord between the branches of a hype=
rbola. Its half-length is the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
emi-major_axis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Semi-major axis">semi-major =
axis</a></i> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</=
span>). When an ellipse or hyperbola are in standard position as in the equ=
ations below, with foci on the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">x</span>-axis and center at the origin, the vertices of the c=
onic have coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=92<i>a</i>, 0)</span>=
 and <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, 0)</span>, with <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> non-negative.
</p><p>The <i>minor axis</i> is the shortest diameter of an ellipse, and it=
s half-length is the <i>semi-minor axis</i> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>), the same value <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> as in the standard equation b=
elow. By analogy, for a hyperbola the parameter <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> in the standard equation is also ca=
lled the semi-minor axis.
</p><p>The following relations hold:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-6"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
