<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Standard_forms_in_Cartesian=
_coordinates">Standard forms in Cartesian coordinates</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_an_ellipse.=
png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_an_ellipse.=
png/330px-Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_an_ellipse.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"310" height=3D"207" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"468" data-file-height=3D"312"></a><figcaption>Standard forms of an elli=
pse</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_parabola.=
png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/77/Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_parabola.=
png/250px-Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_parabola.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"250" height=3D"261" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"1126" data-file-height=3D"1174"></a><figcaption>Standard forms of a par=
abola</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_hyperbola=
.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_hyperbol=
a.png/321px-Conic_section_-_standard_forms_of_a_hyperbola.png" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"310" height=3D"236" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"321" data-file-height=3D"244"></a><figcaption>Standard forms of a hyp=
erbola</figcaption></figure>
<p>After introducing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coo=
rdinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian coordinates=
</a>, the focus-directrix property can be used to produce the equations sat=
isfied by the points of the conic section.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> By means of a change of coordinates (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_of_axes#Rotation_of_conic_sections" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Rotation of axes">rotation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Translation_of_axes#Translation_of_conic_sections" title=
=3D"Translation of axes">translation of axes</a>) these equations can be pu=
t into <i>standard forms</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-8"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 For ellipses and hyperbolas a standard form has the <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>-axis as principal axis and the=
 origin (0,0) as center. The vertices are <span class=3D"texhtml">(=C2=B1<i=
>a</i>, 0)</span> and the foci <span class=3D"texhtml">(=C2=B1<i>c</i>, 0)<=
/span>. Define <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b<=
/span> by the equations <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i=
>a</i><sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 <i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span> for an ellipse and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>a</i><sup>2</sup> + <i=
>b</i><sup>2</sup></span> for a hyperbola. For a circle, <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>c</i> =3D 0</span> so <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup>=
 =3D <i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span>, with <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Radius" title=3D"Radius">radius</a></i> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
r</i> =3D <i>a</i> =3D <i>b</i></span>. For the parabola, the standard form=
 has the focus on the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">x</span>-axis at the point <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, 0)</span=
> and the directrix the line with equation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i>=
 =3D =E2=88=92<i>a</i></span>. In standard form the parabola will always pa=
ss through the origin.
</p><p>For a  <i>rectangular</i> or <i>equilateral</i> hyperbola, one whose=
 asymptotes are perpendicular, there is an alternative standard form in whi=
ch the asymptotes are the coordinate axes and the line <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>y</i></span> is the principal axis. The foci then have =
coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>c</i>, <i>c</i>)</span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=92<i>c</i>, =E2=88=92<i>c</i>)</span>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Con=
ic_section#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Circle:
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e x^{2}+y^{2}=3Da^{2},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>y</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
