<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Polar_coordinates">Polar co=
ordinates</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conics_anim.gif" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/8/88/Conics_anim.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"256" height=3D"256" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"256" data-file-height=3D"256"></a=
><figcaption>Development of the conic section as the eccentricity <i>e</i> =
increases</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system" tit=
le=3D"Polar coordinate system">polar coordinates</a>, a conic section with =
one focus at the origin and, if any, the other at a negative value (for an =
ellipse) or a positive value (for a hyperbola) on the <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>x</i></span>-axis, is given by the equation
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e r=3D{\frac {l}{1+e\cos \theta }},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>l</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mn>1</mn>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>e</mi>
              <mi>cos</mi>
              <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
              <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle r=3D{\frac {l=
}{1+e\cos \theta }},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7831ca98e99a29ebffcd80f8ceb8c0ec0c3ac597" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.171ex; width:15.692ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r=
=3D{\frac {l}{1+e\cos \theta }},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i></span> is the eccentricity and <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>l</i></span> is the semi-latus rectum.
</p><p>As above, for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 0</span>, the gra=
ph is a circle, for <span class=3D"texhtml">0 &lt; <i>e</i> &lt; 1</span> t=
he graph is an ellipse, for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 1</span> a=
 parabola, and for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> &gt; 1</span> a hyperbo=
la.
</p><p>The polar form of the equation of a conic is often used in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamics_(mechanics)" title=3D"Dynamics (=
mechanics)">dynamics</a>; for instance, determining the orbits of objects r=
evolving about the Sun.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-21"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Properties">Properties</h3>=
</div>
<p>Just as two (distinct) points determine a line, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Five_points_determine_a_conic" title=3D"Five points determ=
ine a conic">five points determine a conic</a>. Formally, given any five po=
ints in the plane in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_linea=
r_position" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"General linear position">general=
 linear position</a>, meaning no three <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">collinear</a>, there is a u=
nique conic passing through them, which will be non-degenerate; this is tru=
e in both the Euclidean plane and its extension, the real projective plane.=
 Indeed, given any five points there is a conic passing through them, but i=
f three of the points are collinear the conic will be degenerate (reducible=
, because it contains a line), and may not be unique; see <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degenerate_conic#Points_to_define" title=3D"Degener=
ate conic">further discussion</a>.
</p><p>Four points in the plane in general linear position determine a uniq=
ue conic passing through the first three points and having the fourth point=
 as its center. Thus knowing the center is equivalent to knowing two points=
 on the conic for the purpose of determining the curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
WW_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic=
_section#cite_note-WW-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Furthermore, a conic is determined by any combination of <i>k</i> po=
ints in general position that it passes through and 5 =E2=80=93 <i>k</i> li=
nes that are tangent to it, for 0=E2=89=A4<i>k</i>=E2=89=A45.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coni=
c_section#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Any point in the plane is on either zero, one or two <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tang=
ent line">tangent lines</a> of a conic. A point on just one tangent line is=
 on the conic. A point on no tangent line is said to be an <i>interior poin=
t</i> (or inner point) of the conic, while a point on two tangent lines is =
an <i>exterior point</i> (or outer point).
</p><p>All the conic sections share a <i>reflection property</i> that can b=
e stated as: All mirrors in the shape of a non-degenerate conic section ref=
lect light coming from or going toward one focus toward or away from the ot=
her focus. In the case of the parabola, the second focus needs to be though=
t of as infinitely far away, so that the light rays going toward or coming =
from the second focus are parallel.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-24"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal%27s_theorem" title=
=3D"Pascal's theorem">Pascal's theorem</a> concerns the collinearity of thr=
ee points that are constructed from a set of six points on any non-degenera=
te conic. The theorem also holds for degenerate conics consisting of two li=
nes, but in that case it is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pappus%27s_hexagon_theorem" title=3D"Pappus's hexagon theorem">Pappus's =
theorem</a>.
</p><p>Non-degenerate conic sections are always "<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Smoothness" title=3D"Smoothness">smooth</a>". This is import=
ant for many applications, such as aerodynamics, where a smooth surface is =
required to ensure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laminar_flow" t=
itle=3D"Laminar flow">laminar flow</a> and to prevent <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbulence" title=3D"Turbulence">turbulence</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Menaechmus_and_early_works"=
>Menaechmus and early works</h3></div>
<p>It is believed that the first definition of a conic section was given by=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menaechmus" title=3D"Menaechmus">=
Menaechmus</a> (died 320 BC) as part of his solution of the Delian problem =
(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duplicating_the_cube" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Duplicating the cube">Duplicating the cube</a>).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Conic_section#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-=
27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> His work did not survive, not even the names he used for th=
ese curves, and is only known through secondary accounts.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_se=
ction#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The definition used at that time differs fr=
om the one commonly used today. Cones were constructed by rotating a right =
triangle about one of its legs so the hypotenuse generates the surface of t=
he cone (such a line is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/=
generatrix" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:generatrix">generatrix</a>). Thre=
e types of cones were determined by their vertex angles (measured by twice =
the angle formed by the hypotenuse and the leg being rotated about in the r=
ight triangle). The conic section was then determined by intersecting one o=
f these cones with a plane drawn perpendicular to a generatrix. The type of=
 the conic is determined by the type of cone, that is, by the angle formed =
at the vertex of the cone: If the angle is acute then the conic is an ellip=
se; if the angle is right then the conic is a parabola; and if the angle is=
 obtuse then the conic is a hyperbola (but only one branch of the curve).<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Eu=
clid</a> (fl. 300 BC) is said to have written four books on conics but thes=
e were lost as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archim=
edes</a> (died <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:no=
wrap;">=E2=80=89212</span> BC) is known to have studied conics, having dete=
rmined the area bounded by a parabola and a chord in <i>Quadrature of the P=
arabola</i>. His main interest was in terms of measuring areas and volumes =
of figures related to the conics and part of this work survives in his book=
 on the solids of revolution of conics, <i>On Conoids and Spheroids</i>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Apollonius_of_Perga">Apollo=
nius of Perga</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Conica_of_Apollonius_of_Perga=
_fol._6b-7a_DETAIL.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Conica_of_Apollonius_of_Pe=
rga_fol._6b-7a_DETAIL.jpg/330px-Conica_of_Apollonius_of_Perga_fol._6b-7a_DE=
TAIL.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"193" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"388" data-file-height=3D"241"></a><figcaption>D=
iagram from Apollonius' <i>Conics</i>, in a 9th-century Arabic translation<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>The greatest progress in the study of conics by the ancient Greeks is du=
e to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_of_Perga" title=3D=
"Apollonius of Perga">Apollonius of Perga</a> (died <abbr title=3D"circa">c=
.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89190</span> BC), whose =
eight-volume <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_of_Perga#C=
onics" title=3D"Apollonius of Perga"><i>Conic Sections</i> or <i>Conics</i>=
</a> summarized and greatly extended existing knowledge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_sec=
tion#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Apollonius's study of the properties of thes=
e curves made it possible to show that any plane cutting a fixed double con=
e (two napped), regardless of its angle, will produce a conic according to =
the earlier definition, leading to the definition commonly used today. Circ=
les, not constructible by the earlier method, are also obtainable in this w=
ay. This may account for why Apollonius considered circles a fourth type of=
 conic section, a distinction that is no longer made. Apollonius used the n=
ames 'ellipse', 'parabola' and 'hyperbola' for these curves, borrowing the =
terminology from earlier Pythagorean work on areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#=
cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pappus_of_Alexandria" title=
=3D"Pappus of Alexandria">Pappus of Alexandria</a> (died <abbr title=3D"cir=
ca">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89350</span> AD) is=
 credited with expounding on the importance of the concept of a conic's foc=
us, and detailing the related concept of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Conic_section#Eccentricity,_focus_and_directrix">directrix</a>, in=
cluding the case of the parabola (which is lacking in Apollonius's known wo=
rks).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Islamic_world">Islamic worl=
d</h3></div>
<p>Apollonius's work was translated into Arabic, and much of his work only =
survives through the Arabic version. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Islamic_mathematicians" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Islamic mathemati=
cians">Islamic mathematicians</a> found applications of the theory, most no=
tably the Persian mathematician and poet <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Omar_Khayy%C3%A1m" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Omar Khayy=C3=A1m"=
>Omar Khayy=C3=A1m</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-35"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 who found a geometrical method of solving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Cubic_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cubic equations">c=
ubic equations</a> using conic sections.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-3=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A century before the more famous work of Khayyam, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abu_al-Jud" title=3D"Abu al-Jud">Abu al-Jud</a> used=
 conics to solve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartic_function"=
 title=3D"Quartic function">quartic</a> and cubic equations,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic=
_section#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although his solution did not deal wit=
h all the cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An instrument for drawing conic sections was first described in 1000=
 AD by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ab%C5%AB_Sahl_al-Q%C5%ABh%C=
4%AB" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ab=C5=AB Sahl al-Q=C5=ABh=C4=AB">Al-Ku=
hi</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_sec=
tion#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Europe">Europe</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Table_of_Conics,_Cyclopaedia,=
_volume_1,_p_304,_1728.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Table_of_Conics%2C_Cyc=
lopaedia%2C_volume_1%2C_p_304%2C_1728.jpg/250px-Table_of_Conics%2C_Cyclopae=
dia%2C_volume_1%2C_p_304%2C_1728.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" heig=
ht=3D"398" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1642" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"2614"></a><figcaption>Table of conics, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Cyclopaedia,_or_an_Universal_Dictionary_of_Arts_and_Sciences=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyclopaedia, or an Universal Dictionary of=
 Arts and Sciences">Cyclopaedia</a></i>, 1728</figcaption></figure><p><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepl=
er">Johannes Kepler</a> extended the theory of conics through the "<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_function#Geometric_continuity" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Smooth function">principle of continuity</a>", =
a precursor to the concept of limits. Kepler first used the term 'foci' in =
1604.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girard_Desargues" title=3D"=
Girard Desargues">Girard Desargues</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Blaise_Pascal" title=3D"Blaise Pascal">Blaise Pascal</a> developed=
 a theory of conics using an early form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Projective_geometry" title=3D"Projective geometry">projective geom=
etry</a> and this helped to provide impetus for the study of this new field=
. In particular, Pascal discovered a theorem known as the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexagrammum_mysticum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Hexagrammum mysticum">hexagrammum mysticum</a> from which many other pr=
operties of conics can be deduced.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=
=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Fermat" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pierre Fer=
mat">Pierre Fermat</a> both applied their newly discovered <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">ana=
lytic geometry</a> to the study of conics. This had the effect of reducing =
the geometrical problems of conics to problems in algebra. However, it was =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wallis" title=3D"John Wallis"=
>John Wallis</a> in his 1655 treatise <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><=
i lang=3D"la">Tractatus de sectionibus conicis</i></span> who first defined=
 the conic sections as instances of equations of second degree.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
nic_section#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Written earlier, but published later,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_de_Witt" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Jan de Witt">Jan de Witt</a>'s <span title=3D"Latin-language tex=
t"><i lang=3D"la">Elementa Curvarum Linearum</i></span> starts with Kepler'=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinematics" title=3D"Kinematics"=
>kinematic</a> construction of the conics and then develops the algebraic e=
quations. This work, which uses Fermat's methodology and Descartes' notatio=
n has been described as the first textbook on the subject.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-BoyerDeWitt_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-BoyerDeWitt-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> De Witt invented=
 the term 'directrix'.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BoyerDeWitt_44-1" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-Boyer=
DeWitt-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
For specific applications of each type of conic section, see <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">Circle</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellipse">Ellipse</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">Parabola</=
a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperb=
ola">Hyperbola</a>.</div>
<p>Conic sections are important in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>: the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Orbit" title=3D"Orbit">orbits</a> of two massive objects t=
hat interact according to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravity"=
 title=3D"Gravity">Newton's law of universal gravitation</a> are conic sect=
ions if their common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_of_mas=
s" title=3D"Center of mass">center of mass</a> is considered to be at rest.=
 If they are bound together, they will both trace out ellipses; if they are=
 moving apart, they will both follow parabolas or hyperbolas. See <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-body_problem" title=3D"Two-body probl=
em">two-body problem</a>.
</p><p>The reflective properties of the conic sections are used in the desi=
gn of searchlights, radio-telescopes and some optical telescopes.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Conic_section#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A searchlight uses a parabolic mirr=
or as the reflector, with a bulb at the focus; and a similar construction i=
s used for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabolic_microphone"=
 title=3D"Parabolic microphone">parabolic microphone</a>. The 4.2 meter <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Herschel_Telescope" title=3D"=
William Herschel Telescope">Herschel optical telescope</a> on La Palma, in =
the Canary islands, uses a primary parabolic mirror to reflect light toward=
s a secondary hyperbolic mirror, which reflects it again to a focus behind =
the first mirror.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_the_real_projective_plan=
e">In the real projective plane</h2></div>
<p>The conic sections have some very similar properties in the Euclidean pl=
ane and the reasons for this become clearer when the conics are viewed from=
 the perspective of a larger geometry. The Euclidean plane may be embedded =
in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_projective_plane" titl=
e=3D"Real projective plane">real projective plane</a> and the conics may be=
 considered as objects in this projective geometry. One way to do this is t=
o introduce <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinate=
s" title=3D"Homogeneous coordinates">homogeneous coordinates</a> and define=
 a conic to be the set of points whose coordinates satisfy an irreducible q=
uadratic equation in three variables (or equivalently, the zeros of an irre=
ducible <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_form" title=3D"Q=
uadratic form">quadratic form</a>). More technically, the set of points tha=
t are zeros of a quadratic form (in any number of variables) is called a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadric" title=3D"Quadric">quadric</=
a>, and the irreducible quadrics in a two dimensional projective space (tha=
t is, having three variables) are traditionally called conics.
</p><p>The Euclidean plane <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i><sup>2</sup></sp=
an> is embedded in the real projective plane by adjoining a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_at_infinity" title=3D"Line at infinity">line=
 at infinity</a> (and its corresponding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Point_at_infinity" title=3D"Point at infinity">points at infinity</a>=
) so that all the lines of a parallel class meet on this line. On the other=
 hand, starting with the real projective plane, a Euclidean plane is obtain=
ed by distinguishing some line as the line at infinity and removing it and =
all its points.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Intersection_at_infinity">I=
ntersection at infinity</h3></div>
<p>In a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_space" title=3D=
"Projective space">projective space</a> over any division ring, but in part=
icular over either the real or complex numbers, all non-degenerate conics a=
re equivalent, and thus in projective geometry one speaks of "a conic" with=
out specifying a type. That is, there is a projective transformation that w=
ill map any non-degenerate conic to any other non-degenerate conic.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Conic_section#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The three types of conic sections will reappear in the affine plane =
obtained by choosing a line of the projective space to be the line at infin=
ity. The three types are then determined by how this line at infinity inter=
sects the conic in the projective space. In the corresponding affine space,=
 one obtains an ellipse if the conic does not intersect the line at infinit=
y, a parabola if the conic intersects the line at infinity in one <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Double point">double point</a> corresponding to the axis, and a hyperbo=
la if the conic intersects the line at infinity in two points corresponding=
 to the asymptotes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Homogeneous_coordinates">Ho=
mogeneous coordinates</h3></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinates" tit=
le=3D"Homogeneous coordinates">homogeneous coordinates</a> a conic section =
can be represented as:
</p>
