<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Projective_definition_of_a_=
circle">Projective definition of a circle</h3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_space" title=3D"Metric s=
pace">Metrical</a> concepts of Euclidean geometry (concepts concerned with =
measuring lengths and angles) can not be immediately extended to the real p=
rojective plane.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They must =
be redefined (and generalized) in this new geometry. This can be done for a=
rbitrary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_plane" title=
=3D"Projective plane">projective planes</a>, but to obtain the real project=
ive plane as the extended Euclidean plane, some specific choices have to be=
 made.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Fix an arbitrary line in a projective plane that shall be referred t=
o as the <i>absolute line</i>. Select two distinct points on the absolute l=
ine and refer to them as <i>absolute points</i>. Several metrical concepts =
can be defined with reference to these choices. For instance, given a line =
containing the points <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>B</span>, the <i>midpoint</i> of line segment <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">AB</span> is defined as the point <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span> which is the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_harmonic_conjugate" title=3D"=
Projective harmonic conjugate">projective harmonic conjugate</a> of the poi=
nt of intersection of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">AB</span> and the absolute line, with respect to <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>.
</p><p>A conic in a projective plane that contains the two absolute points =
is called a <i>circle</i>. Since five points determine a conic, a circle (w=
hich may be degenerate) is determined by three points. To obtain the extend=
ed Euclidean plane, the absolute line is chosen to be the line at infinity =
of the Euclidean plane and the absolute points are two special points on th=
at line called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_points=
_at_infinity" title=3D"Circular points at infinity">circular points at infi=
nity</a>. Lines containing two points with real coordinates do not pass thr=
ough the circular points at infinity, so in the Euclidean plane a circle, u=
nder this definition, is determined by three points that are not <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collinear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Co=
llinear">collinear</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-51"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It has been mentioned that circles in the Euclidean plane can not be=
 defined by the focus-directrix property. However, if one were to consider =
the line at infinity as the directrix, then by taking the eccentricity to b=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i> =3D 0</span> a circle will have the focu=
s-directrix property, but it is still not defined by that property.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Conic_section#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One must be careful in this situ=
ation to correctly use the definition of eccentricity as the ratio of the d=
istance of a point on the circle to the focus (length of a radius) to the d=
istance of that point to the directrix (this distance is infinite) which gi=
ves the limiting value of zero.
</p>
