-align: -0.671ex; width:4.604ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U,V=
}"></span> only the images of 3 lines have to be given. These 5 items (2 po=
ints, 3 lines) uniquely determine the conic section.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Line_conics">Line conics</h=
3></div>
<p>By the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duality_(projective_geom=
etry)" title=3D"Duality (projective geometry)">Principle of Duality</a> in =
a projective plane, the dual of each point is a line, and the dual of a loc=
us of points (a set of points satisfying some condition) is called an <i>en=
velope</i> of lines. Using Steiner's definition of a conic (this locus of p=
oints will now be referred to as a <i>point conic</i>) as the meet of corre=
sponding rays of two related pencils, it is easy to dualize and obtain the =
corresponding envelope consisting of the joins of corresponding points of t=
wo related ranges (points on a line) on different bases (the lines the poin=
ts are on). Such an envelope is called a <i>line conic</i> (or dual conic).
</p><p>In the real projective plane, a point conic has the property that ev=
ery line meets it in two points (which may coincide, or may be complex) and=
 any set of points with this property is a point conic. It follows dually t=
hat a line conic has two of its lines through every point and any envelope =
of lines with this property is a line conic. At every point of a point coni=
c there is a unique tangent line, and dually, on every line of a line conic=
 there is a unique point called a <i>point of contact</i>. An important the=
orem states that the tangent lines of a point conic form a line conic, and =
dually, the points of contact of a line conic form a point conic.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Conic_section#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Von_Staudt's_definition"><s=
pan id=3D"Von_Staudt.27s_definition"></span>Von Staudt's definition</h3></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Staudt_conic" ti=
tle=3D"Von Staudt conic">Von Staudt conic</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Georg_Christian_von_Staudt=
" title=3D"Karl Georg Christian von Staudt">Karl Georg Christian von Staudt=
</a> defined a conic as the point set given by all the absolute points of a=
 <i>polarity</i> that has absolute points. Von Staudt introduced this defin=
ition in <i>Geometrie der Lage</i> (1847) as part of his attempt to remove =
all metrical concepts from projective geometry.
</p><p>A <i>polarity</i>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">=CF=80</span>, of a projective plane <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>P</i></span> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Involution_(mathematics)" title=3D"Involution (mathematics=
)">involutory</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bijection" title=
=3D"Bijection">bijection</a> between the points and the lines of <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>P</i></span> that preser=
ves the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incidence_(geometry)" titl=
e=3D"Incidence (geometry)">incidence relation</a>. Thus, a polarity associa=
tes a point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>Q<=
/i></span> with a line <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;"><i>q</i></span> by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=80</i>(<i>Q</i>) =
=3D <i>q</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=80</i>(<i>q</i>) =3D=
 <i>Q</i></span>. Following <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gergon=
ne" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gergonne">Gergonne</a>, <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>q</i></span> is called the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pole_and_polar" title=3D"Pole and pol=
ar"><i>polar</i></a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;"><i>Q</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;"><i>Q</i></span> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pole=
_and_polar" title=3D"Pole and polar"><i>pole</i></a> of <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>q</i></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_sect=
ion#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An <i>absolute point</i> (or <i>line</i>) of =
a polarity is one which is incident with its polar (pole).<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_s=
ection#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>e<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A von Staudt conic in the real projective plane is equivalent to a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steiner_conic" title=3D"Steiner con=
ic">Steiner conic</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-61"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Constructions">Construction=
s</h3></div>
<p>No continuous arc of a conic can be constructed with straightedge and co=
mpass. However, there are several straightedge-and-compass constructions fo=
r any number of individual points on an arc.
</p><p>One of them is based on the converse of Pascal's theorem, namely, <i=
>if the points of intersection of opposite sides of a hexagon are collinear=
, then the six vertices lie on a conic.</i> Specifically, given five points=
, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i>, <i>B</i>, <i>C</i>, <i>D</i>, <i>E</i><=
/span> and a line passing through <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">E</span>, say <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-=
decoration:overline;"><i>EG</i></span></span>, a point <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> that lies on this line and i=
s on the conic determined by the five points can be constructed. Let <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>AB</i></span=
></span> meet <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overli=
ne;"><i>DE</i></span></span> in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">L</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decora=
tion:overline;"><i>BC</i></span></span> meet <span class=3D"texhtml"><span =
style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>EG</i></span></span> in <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">M</span> and let <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>CD</i></span></sp=
an> meet <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">=
<i>LM</i></span></span> at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">N</span>. Then <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decora=
tion:overline;"><i>AN</i></span></span> meets <span class=3D"texhtml"><span=
 style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>EG</i></span></span> at the require=
d point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By varying the line throu=
gh <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">E</span>, as m=
any additional points on the conic as desired can be constructed.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ellipse_construction_-_parallelogram_method.g=
if" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Ellipse_construction_-_parallelogram_method.gi=
f/250px-Ellipse_construction_-_parallelogram_method.gif" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
400" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>Parallelogram method for cons=
tructing an ellipse</figcaption></figure>
<p>Another method, based on Steiner's construction and which is useful in e=
ngineering applications, is the parallelogram method, where a conic is cons=
tructed point by point by means of connecting certain equally spaced points=
 on a horizontal line and a vertical line.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note=
-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Specifically, to construct the ellipse with equation <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><spa=
n class=3D"num"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span>=
<span class=3D"den"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> + <l=
ink rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r12=
14402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=
=3D"num"><i>y</i><sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span c=
lass=3D"den"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> =3D 1</span=
>, first construct the rectangle <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ABCD</i></span>=
 with vertices <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i>(<i>a</i>, 0), <i>B</i>(<i>a=
</i>, 2<i>b</i>), <i>C</i>(=E2=88=92<i>a</i>, 2<i>b</i>)</span> and  <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i>(=E2=88=92<i>a</i>, 0)</span>. Divide the side <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>BC</i></=
span></span> into <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>n</span> equal segments and use parallel projection, with respect to the d=
iagonal <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><=
i>AC</i></span></span>, to form equal segments on side <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>AB</i></span></span> (the =
lengths of these segments will be <span class=3D"texhtml"><link rel=3D"mw-d=
eduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span=
 class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>b</i>=
</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den"><i>a</i></span><=
/span>=E2=81=A0</span></span> times the length of the segments on <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>BC</i></span></=
span>). On the side <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:=
overline;"><i>BC</i></span></span> label the left-hand endpoints of the seg=
ments with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>1</sub></span> to <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sub>n</sub></span> starting at <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> and going towards <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">C</span>. On the side <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>AB</i></spa=
n></span> label the upper endpoints <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i><sub>1<=
/sub></span> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i><sub>n</sub></span> startin=
g at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and=
 going towards <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B<=
/span>. The points of intersection, <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"=
text-decoration:overline;"><i>AA</i></span><sub>i</sub> =E2=88=A9 <span sty=
le=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>DD</i></span><sub>i</sub></span> for <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">1 =E2=89=A4 <i>i</i> =E2=89=A4 <i>n</i></span> will b=
e points of the ellipse between <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i>(0, <i>b</i>)</=
span>. The labeling associates the lines of the pencil through <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> with the lines of t=
he pencil through <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>D</span> projectively but not perspectively. The sought for conic is obtai=
ned by this construction since three points <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i=
>, <i>D</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">P</span> and two tangents (the vertical lines at <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span>) uniquely determine the conic. I=
f another diameter (and its conjugate diameter) are used instead of the maj=
or and minor axes of the ellipse, a parallelogram that is not a rectangle i=
s used in the construction, giving the name of the method. The association =
of lines of the pencils can be extended to obtain other points on the ellip=
se. The constructions for hyperbolas<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-64"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and parabolas<sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-65"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 are similar.
</p><p>Yet another general method uses the polarity property to construct t=
he tangent envelope of a conic (a line conic).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_=
note-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_the_complex_geometry">In=
 the complex geometry</h2></div>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_coordinate_plane=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex coordinate plane">complex coordina=
