{2}-w^{2}=3D1}"></span>. Thus there is a 2-way classification: ellipse/hype=
rbola and parabola. Extending the curves to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Complex_projective_plane" title=3D"Complex projective plane">=
complex projective plane</a>, this corresponds to intersecting the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_at_infinity" title=3D"Line at infini=
ty">line at infinity</a> in either 2 distinct points (corresponding to two =
asymptotes) or in 1 double point (corresponding to the axis of a parabola);=
 thus the real hyperbola is a more suggestive real image for the complex el=
lipse/hyperbola, as it also has 2 (real) intersections with the line at inf=
inity.
</p><p>Further unification occurs in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_projective_plane" title=3D"Complex projective plane">complex=
 projective plane</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>CP</b><sup>2</sup></span>:=
 the non-degenerate conics cannot be distinguished from one another, since =
any can be taken to any other by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Projective_linear_transformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Projectiv=
e linear transformation">projective linear transformation</a>.
</p><p>It can be proven that in <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>CP</b><sup>2</su=
p></span>, two conic sections have four points in common (if one accounts f=
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicity_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Multiplicity (mathematics)">multiplicity</a>), so there are between 1=
 and 4 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_theorem" ti=
tle=3D"B=C3=A9zout's theorem">intersection</a> points. The intersection pos=
sibilities are: four distinct points, two singular points and one double po=
int, two double points, one singular point and one with multiplicity 3, one=
 point with multiplicity 4. If any intersection point has multiplicity &gt;=
 1, the two curves are said to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Tangent" title=3D"Tangent">tangent</a>. If there is an intersection point o=
f multiplicity at least 3, the two curves are said to be <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osculating_curve" title=3D"Osculating curve">osculat=
ing</a>. If there is only one intersection point, which has multiplicity 4,=
 the two curves are said to be <i>superosculating</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6=
7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_secti=
on#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Furthermore, each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Straight_=
line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Straight line">straight line</a> inter=
sects each conic section twice. If the intersection point is double, the li=
ne is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent_line" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Tangent line">tangent line</a>.
Intersecting with the line at infinity, each conic section has two points a=
t infinity. If these points are real, the curve is a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbola" title=3D"Hyperbola">hyperbola</a>; if they ar=
e imaginary conjugates, it is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
llipse" title=3D"Ellipse">ellipse</a>; if there is only one double point, i=
t is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola=
">parabola</a>. If the points at infinity are the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_points" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyclic points=
">cyclic points</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">[1: <i>i</i>: 0]</span> and <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">[1: =E2=80=93<i>i</i>: 0]</span>, the conic section is=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle=
</a>. If the coefficients of a conic section are real, the points at infini=
ty are either real or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_conj=
ugate" title=3D"Complex conjugate">complex conjugate</a>.
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Degenerate_conics"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Degenerate_cases">Degenerat=
e cases</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degenerate_co=
nic" title=3D"Degenerate conic">Degenerate conic</a></div>
<p>What should be considered as a <i>degenerate</i> case of a conic depends=
 on the definition being used and the geometric setting for the conic secti=
on. There are some authors who define a conic as a two-dimensional nondegen=
erate quadric. With this terminology there are no degenerate conics (only d=
egenerate quadrics), but we shall use the more traditional terminology and =
avoid that definition.
</p><p>In the Euclidean plane, using the geometric definition, a degenerate=
 case arises when the cutting plane passes through the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apex_(geometry)" title=3D"Apex (geometry)">apex</a> of=
 the cone.
The degenerate conic is either: a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Point_(geometry)" title=3D"Point (geometry)">point</a>, when the plane inte=
rsects the cone only at the apex; a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Straight_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Straight line">straight lin=
e</a>, when the plane is tangent to the cone (it contains exactly one gener=
ator of the cone); or a pair of intersecting lines (two generators of the c=
one).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These correspond res=
pectively to the limiting forms of an ellipse, parabola, and a hyperbola.
</p><p>If a conic in the Euclidean plane is being defined by the zeros of a=
 quadratic equation (that is, as a quadric), then the degenerate conics are=
: the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empty_set" title=3D"Empty se=
t">empty set</a>, a point, or a pair of lines which may be parallel, inters=
ect at a point, or coincide. The empty set case may correspond either to a =
pair of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_conjugate" title=
=3D"Complex conjugate">complex conjugate</a> parallel lines such as with th=
e equation <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span c=
lass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none=
;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displays=
tyle x^{2}+1=3D0,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
