-align: -0.671ex; width:16.35ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x^{=
2}+y^{2}+1=3D0.}"></span> An imaginary ellipse does not satisfy the general=
 definition of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degeneracy_(mathe=
matics)" title=3D"Degeneracy (mathematics)">degeneracy</a>, and is thus not=
 normally considered as degenerated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-69"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The two lines case occurs when the quadratic expression factors =
into two linear factors, the zeros of each giving a line. In the case that =
the factors are the same, the corresponding lines coincide and we refer to =
the line as
a <i>double</i> line (a line with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Multiplicity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Multiplicity (mathematics)">multiplici=
ty</a> 2) and this is the previous case of a tangent cutting plane.
</p><p>In the real projective plane, since parallel lines meet at a point o=
n the line at infinity, the parallel line case of the Euclidean plane can b=
e viewed as intersecting lines. However, as the point of intersection is th=
e apex of the cone, the cone itself degenerates to a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cyli=
nder (geometry)">cylinder</a>, i.e. with the apex at infinity. Other sectio=
ns in this case are called <i>cylindric sections</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_sectio=
n#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The non-degenerate cylindrical sections are ell=
ipses (or circles).
</p><p>When viewed from the perspective of the complex projective plane, th=
e degenerate cases of a real quadric (i.e., the quadratic equation has real=
 coefficients) can all be considered as a pair of lines, possibly coincidin=
g. The empty set may be the line at infinity considered as a double line, a=
 (real) point is the intersection of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_conjugate_line" title=3D"Complex conjugate line">complex con=
jugate lines</a> and the other cases as previously mentioned.
</p><p>To distinguish the degenerate cases from the non-degenerate cases (i=
ncluding the empty set with the latter) using matrix notation, let <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B2</i></span> be the determinant of the 3=E2=80=89=
=C3=97=E2=80=893 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_representa=
tion_of_conic_sections" title=3D"Matrix representation of conic sections">m=
atrix of the conic section</a>=E2=80=94that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
=CE=B2 </i> =3D (<i>AC</i> =E2=88=92 <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-st=
yle" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=
=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>B</i><sup>2</sup></span><=
span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0=
</span>)<i>F</i> + <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-da=
ta:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=
=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>BED</i> =E2=88=92 <i>CD</i><sup>2</sup> =
=E2=88=92 <i>AE</i><sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span=
 class=3D"den">4</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span></span>; and let <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> =3D <i>B</i><sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4<i>AC</i></s=
pan> be the discriminant. Then the conic section is non-degenerate if and o=
nly if <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B2</i> =E2=89=A0 0</span>.  If <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B2 </i>=3D 0</span> we have a point when <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> &lt; 0</span>, two parallel lines (possibly co=
inciding) when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> =3D 0</span>, or two i=
ntersecting lines when <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i> &gt; 0</span>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Pencil_of_conics">Pencil of=
 conics</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pencil_(mathematics)=
#Pencil_of_conics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pencil (mathematics)">Pen=
cil (mathematics) =C2=A7&nbsp;Pencil of conics</a></div>
<p>A (non-degenerate) conic is completely determined by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Five_points_determine_a_conic" title=3D"Five points d=
etermine a conic">five points</a> in general position (no three <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collinear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Col=
linear">collinear</a>) in a plane and the system of conics which pass throu=
gh a fixed set of four points (again in a plane and no three collinear) is =
called a <i>pencil of conics</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_note-72"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The four common points are called the <i>base points</i> of the pen=
cil. Through any point other than a base point, there passes a single conic=
 of the pencil. This concept generalizes a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pencil_(mathematics)#Pencil_of_circles" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Pencil (mathematics)">pencil of circles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#ci=
te_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Intersecting_two_conics">In=
tersecting two conics</h2></div>
<p>The solutions to a system of two second degree equations in two variable=
s may be viewed as the coordinates of the points of intersection of two gen=
eric conic sections.
In particular two conics may possess none, two or four possibly coincident =
intersection points.
An efficient method of locating these solutions exploits the homogeneous <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_representation_of_conic_secti=
ons" title=3D"Matrix representation of conic sections">matrix representatio=
n of conic sections</a>, i.e. a 3=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=893 <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_matrix" title=3D"Symmetric matrix">symme=
tric matrix</a> which depends on six parameters.
</p><p>The procedure to locate the intersection points follows these steps,=
 where the conics are represented by matrices:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section#cite_=
note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>given the two conics <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-eleme=
