uation#Linear_equations_of_second_order" title=3D"Partial differential equa=
tion">second order</a> are classified at each point as elliptic, parabolic,=
 or hyperbolic, accordingly as their second order terms correspond to an el=
liptic, parabolic, or hyperbolic quadratic form. The behavior and theory of=
 these different types of PDEs are strikingly different =E2=80=93 represent=
ative examples is that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson=
_equation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Poisson equation">Poisson equatio=
n</a> is elliptic, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_equati=
on" title=3D"Heat equation">heat equation</a> is parabolic, and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave_equation" title=3D"Wave equation">wa=
ve equation</a> is hyperbolic.</dd></dl>
